{
  "id": 52560,
  "kuerzel": "M_TuIT_EVA_1002",
  "bezeichnung": "Introductory optics for photonics",
  "kreditpunkte": 3,
  "lernziele": "<p>At the end of this intensive course the sudents will know the conceptual differences between the three different<br />ways of seeing light: as a ray, as a wave or as quanta (photons).<br />The students will be able to decide which model is best suited for the applications of optics in photonics.</p>",
  "vorausgKenntnisse": "<p>Bachelor-Studium Systemtechnik</p>",
  "semesterBewertung": "Note von 1 - 6",
  "sprache": "",
  "zustand": "deaktiviert",
  "kurse": [
    {
      "id": 52561,
      "kuerzel": "TuIT_EVA_1002",
      "bezeichnung": "Introductory optics for photonics",
      "kreditpunkte": 0,
      "lernziele": "<p><span style=\"display: inline !important; float: none; background-color: transparent; color: #000000; cursor: text; font-family: 'Frutiger_web',Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">At the end of this intensive course the sudents will know the conceptual differences between the three different</span><br style=\"background-color: transparent; box-sizing: border-box; color: #000000; font-family: &amp;quot; frutiger_web&amp;quot;,arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\" /><span style=\"display: inline !important; float: none; background-color: transparent; color: #000000; cursor: text; font-family: 'Frutiger_web',Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">ways of seeing light: as a ray, as a wave or as quanta (photons).</span><br style=\"background-color: transparent; box-sizing: border-box; color: #000000; font-family: &amp;quot; frutiger_web&amp;quot;,arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\" /><span style=\"display: inline !important; float: none; background-color: transparent; color: #000000; cursor: text; font-family: 'Frutiger_web',Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">The students will be able to decide which model is best suited for the applications of optics in photonics.</span></p>",
      "planinhalt": "<p>In particular they will be introduced into the following sub-fields of optics:<br />Part 1 - Geometrical optics</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Basics of geometrical optics (differentiation from wave optics, wave-particle dualism, refractive index,<br />dispersion, Abbe-number, refraction, reflection)</li>\n<li>Optical imaging with lenses</li>\n<li>Thin lenses / Thick lenses</li>\n<li>Apertures</li>\n<li>Mirrors</li>\n<li>Aberrations</li>\n<li>The human eye, magnifying lenses</li>\n<li>Basics of cameras</li>\n<li>Microscope, telescope, teleobjective, zoom-camera -&gt; as exercises</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Part 2 &ndash; Wave optics</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Concept EM-wave</li>\n<li>Maxwell equations and wave equation (incl. rot, div, grad)</li>\n<li>Intensity &amp; pointing Vector</li>\n<li>Polarisation concept (TE, TM, &hellip;)</li>\n<li>&nbsp;Reflection and refraction at an interface &ndash; Fresnel equations</li>\n<li>Interference and Fabry Perot Interferometer</li>\n<li>Diffraction:<br />Frauenhofer diffraction slit/circular aperture<br />Gratings (ref/transmission)<br />Fresnel lens</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Part 3 &ndash; Light matter interaction: Photons and Atoms</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Photons and Atoms</li>\n<li>Interaction of light with bound electrons: mechanisms at the atomic Level</li>\n<li>Interaction of photons with systems of atoms (dielectric materials)</li>\n<li>Interaction of light with free electrons</li>\n<li>Interaction of light with metals</li>\n<li>The Drude model</li>\n</ul>",
      "empfLehrmittel": "<p>Seminar, Blockwoche</p>",
      "leistungsnachweis": "<p><span style=\"display: inline !important; float: none; background-color: transparent; color: #000000; cursor: text; font-family: 'Frutiger_web',Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">1) Exam during semester</span><br style=\"background-color: transparent; box-sizing: border-box; color: #000000; font-family: &amp;quot; frutiger_web&amp;quot;,arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\" /><span style=\"display: inline !important; float: none; background-color: transparent; color: #000000; cursor: text; font-family: 'Frutiger_web',Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-decoration: none; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;\">2) Short report on a topic of choice from optics and photonics. A list of topics will be distributed at the beginning of the course. Own topics are also possible. Due at the end of the 3rd semester week.</span></p>",
